&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot; text-align: left; direction: ltr; unicode-bidi: embed;&quot;&gt;Beginning in 1917, Kafka spent time learning Hebrew, first by himself, and later with various teachers. This is one out of five booklets filled with vocabulary by Kafka and the only one kept at the National Library of Israel.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot; text-align: left; direction: ltr; unicode-bidi: embed;&quot;&gt;In his last years he studied with Pu&apos;ah Ben Tovim, a young student from Jerusalem, who came recommended by his good friend S.H. Bergmann, and was staying as a student in Bergmann&apos;s mother home in Prague. Kafka and Ben-Tovim &amp;#160;were reading the Hebrew novel &lt;i&gt;Breakdown and Bereavement&lt;/i&gt; by Y.H. Brenner, and there are testimonies that he was able to speak and even to write simple letters in Hebrew.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot; text-align: left; direction: ltr; unicode-bidi: embed;&quot;&gt;Some of the words included in this booklet very much remind us of the imaginary world of the author: passion, cockroach, escape, illusion etc.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd&quot;&gt; 
