&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot; text-align: left; direction: ltr; unicode-bidi: embed;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: Arial,sans-serif;&quot;&gt;However, Zweig totally rejected the Zionist movement which strove to create a national home for the Jews in their historical homeland. Zweig believed that being a Jew allowed him to conduct his life according to humanistic values, and refused to join the&quot; fanatical nationalistic movements&quot;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot; text-align: left; direction: ltr; unicode-bidi: embed;&quot;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: Arial,sans-serif;&quot;&gt;In his letter &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: Arial,sans-serif;&quot;&gt;to the famous Jewish philosopher Martin Buber, written on 24.1.1917 during the midst of WWI, Zweig expounded on his attitude towards Judaism and Zionism. Among other things Zweig also mentioned the &quot;fanatic and nationalistic views&quot; of Kafka&apos;s close friend, Max Brod.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

