&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot; text-align: left; direction: ltr; unicode-bidi: embed;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: Arial,sans-serif;&quot;&gt;Zweig&apos;s autobiography, &lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: Arial,sans-serif;&quot;&gt;The World of Yesterday&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: Arial,sans-serif;&quot;&gt;, preserves not only the memories of Zweig&apos;s life, but the memories of the cultural era, from the end of the 19th century to the onset of WWII. Zweig describes his days as a young boy, his experiences as a student, and the support he received from Theodore Herzl as a young and promising writer. Zweig does not only glorify this era, but expressly points out its drawbacks.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: Arial,sans-serif;&quot;&gt;The typescript of the book in the NLI is the only existing copy which is intact. It also contains corrections made by Zweig&apos;s wife, Lotte. The copy was donated to the NLI by the translator of Zweig&apos;s works into Spanish, Alfredo Cahn, who lives in Argentina.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd&quot;&gt;&lt;html xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml&quot;&gt;
