&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: small;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-family: Arial;&quot;&gt;The Guide of the Perplexed, an important philosophical treatise, composed between 1185-1191, is set as a letter to a young disciple. The Guide sought to resolve apparent contradictions between rationalist philosophy, on the one hand, and Jewish tradition found in Scripture and the Talmud, on the other hand.&amp;#160; Unlike the &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: small;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-family: Arial;&quot;&gt;Mishneh Torah&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: small;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-family: Arial;&quot;&gt;, which was written for broad use, the &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: small;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-family: Arial;&quot;&gt;Guide&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: small;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-family: Arial;&quot;&gt;, written in Judeo-Arabic, was written for a more limited audience of rationalist, yet traditional Jews. A few of Maimonides&#8217; theological positions led to public controversies with Rabbinic leaders outside of Egypt towards the end of his life.&amp;#160;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

