&lt;/style&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot; margin-left: -7.1pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; color: black; background: white;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: small;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-family: Arial;&quot;&gt;Kabbalah&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; color: black; background: white;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: small;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-family: Arial;&quot;&gt; in general, and especially the &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: small;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-family: Arial;&quot;&gt;Zohar&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: small;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-family: Arial;&quot;&gt;, was considered by many a doctrine which could only be correctly understood by scholars who are well versed in Jewish sources. After Sabbateanism, the fact that Kabbalah delved into basic questions regarding the nature of the divine caused it to be conceived as a dangerous doctrine which might lead simple believers astray. Thus, the study of Kabbalah was usually forbidden to people below the age of forty and to those who were not learned.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: small;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-family: Arial;&quot;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot; margin-left: -7.1pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; color: black; background: white;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: small;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-family: Arial;&quot;&gt;The invention of the printing press, helped remove the restrictions which had been imposed on the dissemination and study of Kabbalah.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

