--&gt;
&lt;/style&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot; text-align: left; direction: ltr; unicode-bidi: embed;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; line-height: 115%;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: small;&quot;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-family: Arial;&quot;&gt;Although born to Jewish parents, religion did not play a central role in Zweig&apos;s education.&amp;#160; When asked about this in an interview, Zweig said: &quot;My mother and father were Jewish only through accident of birth&quot;. Zweig believed in universalism and Europeanism and adopted Judaism only inasmuch as it supported these ideas. However, he did not renounce his Jewish faith and wrote repeatedly on Jews and Jewish themes - such as in his story &lt;i&gt;Buchmendel&lt;/i&gt; - and his Jewish identity clearly played a significant role in his life: &#8220;I have been vitally interested in Jewish problems all my life,&#8221; he wrote, &#8220;vitally aware of the Jewish blood that is in me ever since I have been conscious of it.&quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd&quot;&gt; 
