&lt;body&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;DefaultStyle&quot; align=&quot;left&quot; style=&quot; text-align: left;&quot;&gt;In 1160, the family settled in Fez, Morocco which was also under the rule of the Almohads as well, where Maimonides witnessed terrible persecutions.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;DefaultStyle&quot; align=&quot;left&quot; style=&quot; text-align: left;&quot;&gt;It seems that during this period the family was forced to convert.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;DefaultStyle&quot; align=&quot;left&quot; style=&quot; text-align: left;&quot;&gt;This is probably why, sometime between 1160-1165, Maimonides wrote &lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;The Letter on Forced Conversions&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt; which pardoned fake conversion to Islam in cases of forced conversion. &amp;#160;In Fez, Maimonides continued studying medicine, mainly through apprenticeship.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd&quot;&gt; 
