&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;This is the first page of the original manuscript of Benjamin&apos;s work on &lt;i&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 115%; color: black; background: white;&quot;&gt;The Origin of German Tragic Drama&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; color: black; background: white;&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;which he wrote in order to receive his &lt;i&gt;venia legendi&lt;/i&gt; in German universities (habilitation). In this work Benjamin deals with the origins of German tragic drama in the Baroque era by analyzing the texts in a very radical manner. Even before the official reviewing process Benjamin was told that his analysis was regarded too modern and not sufficiently academic. He therefore decided to withdraw his thesis, a step that brought his academic career to a halt. The text was nevertheless published as a book in 1928.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;What was then regarded to be too modern still serves as a source for further research: even today, numerous literary scholars refer to Benjamin&apos;s work and praise him for his extraordinary way of thinking.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

